A spokesman for the zoo said: ‘We were shocked when we first saw Hope.

‘Her
feet were bent in such a way that if she were to stand up it would have
been the equivalent of our feet bent so far forward we would be walking
on our ankles and not our heels.

‘At birth, Hope's front tendons were too tight while the rear tendons in her legs were stretched out too much.

‘The
idea of the shoes was that they could continue to offer some support to
the legs while at the same time allowing her body to begin to use those
legs in a more normal manner.

